  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Here's the breakdown of how Go-Back-N and Selective Repeat ARQ handle acknowledgements:\n\n*   **Go-Back-N ARQ:** Uses **cumulative acknowledgements**.\n\n    *   The receiver acknowledges the *last* correctly received packet in order.\n    *   For example, if the receiver sends ACK 5, it implicitly acknowledges packets 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5.\n    *   If the sender doesn't receive an acknowledgement for a packet within a timeout, it resends that packet and all subsequent packets (that were sent after that unacknowledged packet). This can be inefficient.\n\n*   **Selective Repeat ARQ:** Uses **individual acknowledgements** (also called selective acknowledgements or SACKs).\n\n    *   The receiver acknowledges *each* correctly received packet, regardless of its order.\n    *   The receiver buffers out-of-order packets.\n    *   The sender only retransmits the packets that have not been acknowledged (allowing for more efficient use of bandwidth).\n    *   This requires more sophisticated buffering and management at both the sender and receiver.",
